Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[There are numerous pet birds and exotic and/or rare chickens kept as pets and show animals. Those keeping them as pets know their personalities and genuinely enjoy their pets. It is very sad to think something could happen to their pets. We hope all bird owners will be overly cautious and take extra precautions to keep their birds healthy.

Even those producers who raise backyard eggs would not like losing their investment or their eggs even though they are not emotionally attached to their birds.

Certainly, don't move the birds, as we have seen that the disease was recently transported to Utah for a show, and now some birds there have the disease.

While washing hands and boots before and after entering a containment area is a good idea, it may also be appropriate to wear a mask so that you don't exhale any viral particles if you are coming down with a respiratory or sinus situation.

What is really horrible is how long this has been going on without any plan to protect birds. After the fiasco of huge number of bird deaths in 2003, one has to wonder why scientists, and especially those at universities and government entities, have not been working on vaccine development. Why let this situation repeat itself 16 years later? Why do we not have a vaccine? We have the technology, and it can be and should have been already in the works and ready to deploy. - Mod.TG

